arch:property.oc:show_val: Closing elevation: -2.57 m or 905.421 m at Sub datum I.
Locus 41 floor of the Anteroom; Locus 15 south wall of Anteroom; Locus 10 south facade wall and Locus 13 south terraces.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.
Abandonment of the Shrine Room and modification of the Anteroom's east wall. The doorway between the Anteroom and Shrine Room is blocked. This could also belong to Phase V.
In the southwest of the trench, the west perimeter of Locus 13 south terraces.

The east wall of the Anteroom is composed of seven courses of scavenged building material. Unlike the other walls of the rooms the blocks contain marginal drafts, small stones and irregular blocks. It is undetermined if this wall was built at a later point in antiquity to construct an Anteroom for the Chapel, or if the original wall collapsed because of the stress of the terraces it abuts. The preserved height of the wall is 3.12 m. The northern blocks of the façade wall and the eastern wall have been removed down to the foundation course making it impossible to determine if these features do bond.
Opening elevation: +0.55 m or 908.541 m at Sub datum I.
